{"_id":"JN6ZbILajAthoEBS","name":"Damage","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.ZUjwVA7Mh1wjoKu5"}},"content":"<p>When hit by an attack, compare the damage of the weapon to the Toughness of the target. Armor is already included in Toughness, so players don&rsquo;t need to consider it separately. If damage is 5 or more less than Toughness the attack has no effect at all. If damage is less than Toughness it deals 1 Shock. A character who suffers more Shock than the listed limit is Knocked Out (KOed) and no longer takes turns. If damage is at least equal to Toughness the target suffers 2 Shock. If damage is 5 greater than Toughness the target suffers 2 Shock and 1 Wound (see below). Every +5 damage beyond that does another Wound and another 2 Shock.</p>\n<h3>Wounds</h3>\n<p>Each Wound is a permanent &ndash;1 penalty on all tests. When a Storm Knight suffers more than 3 Wounds they are KOed and must test @Compendium[world.up-the-creek.4hN0xAsql86XWwEY]{Defeat}. Villains like Gospog or regular edeinos are KOed by a single Wound.</p>\n<p>DAMAGE RESULTS TABLE</p>\n<table style=\"width: 77.5796%; height: 223px;\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height: 54px;\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 45.3963%; height: 54px;\">\n<p>Damage</p>\n<p>Over Toughness</p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 53.828%; height: 54px;\">Damage</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 16px;\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 45.3963%; height: 16px;\">-6 or more</td>\n<td style=\"width: 53.828%; height: 16px;\">No effect</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 16px;\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 45.3963%; height: 16px;\">-5 to -1</td>\n<td style=\"width: 53.828%; height: 16px;\">1 Shock</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 16px;\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 45.3963%; height: 16px;\">0-4</td>\n<td style=\"width: 53.828%; height: 16px;\">2 Shock</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 16px;\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 45.3963%; height: 16px;\">5-9</td>\n<td style=\"width: 53.828%; height: 16px;\">1 Wound, 2 Shock</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 16px;\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 45.3963%; height: 16px;\">10-14</td>\n<td style=\"width: 53.828%; height: 16px;\">2 Wounds, 4 Shock</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 16px;\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 45.3963%; height: 16px;\">15-19</td>\n<td style=\"width: 53.828%; height: 16px;\">3 Wounds, 6 Shock</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 16px;\">\n<td style=\"text-align: center; width: 45.3963%; height: 16px;\">20=24</td>\n<td style=\"width: 53.828%; height: 16px;\">4 Wounds, 8 Shock</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>...and so on</p>\n<h3>Bonus Dice</h3>\n<p>A Good success or better on an attack, the Law of Savagery, or a character&rsquo;s individual abilities may earn Bonus Dice (BD) for damage. Start with the attack&rsquo;s normal damage, then click the BD button at the bottom of the chat message that displays the successful attack. This will roll a single BD and add the result to total damage value. Compare this damage value to Toughness. Rolling a &infin; symbol adds +5 to damage AND rolls another BD!</p>\n<p>If your attack generated more than one BD, continue to click the BD button at the bottom of each new chat message until the correct number of BD have been rolled.</p>\n<h3>Soaking Damage</h3>\n<p>When a Storm Knight first takes a Wound, introduce the concept of Soaking damage, the other major use of Possibilities. The character shifts reality, choosing a version of events where the result of the attack is more favorable. Spend 1 Possibility and make a normal DN 10 test against the character&rsquo;s reality skill. On a success the damage from the attack is reduced by 1 Wound, and ALL Shock is ignored. A Good success reduces the damage by 2 Wounds. An Outstanding eliminates all damage, regardless of how many Wounds it would have caused.&nbsp;</p>"}
{"_id":"JO60BtYHQ1K9I7hD","name":"About this Module","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.KZrE4SavM2X0c5yt"}},"content":"<h2>Original Up the Creek Design Team</h2>\n<p><strong>Writing</strong>: Darrell Hayhurst</p>\n<p><strong>Editing</strong>: Ron Blessing</p>\n<p><strong>Art Direction</strong>: Aaron Acevedo</p>\n<p><strong>Layout</strong>: Aaron Acevedo, Darrell Hayhurst</p>\n<p><strong>Graphic Design</strong>: Aaron Acevedo, Jason Engle, Maik Schmidt</p>\n<p><strong>Cover</strong>: Gunship Revolution</p>\n<p><strong>Interior Illustrations</strong>: Chris Bivins, Talon Dunning, Bien Flores, Gunship Revolution, Alida Saxon, Unique Soparie</p>\n<h2>Up the Creek Foundry Module</h2>\n<p>Adapted for the Torg Eternity Foundry system by Matt Ritchie.</p>\n<hr />\n<p><strong>Torg, The Possibility Wars, and all unique characters, concepts, locations, and creatures are trademarks and / or copyrights of Ulisses Spiele. All rights reserved.</strong></p>"}
{"_id":"KTres6vCn1T1KcKO","name":"Drama Cards","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.qxIosmwudMc4tb4O"}},"content":"<p>The conflict line on a Drama Card may contain a special condition that applies to one of the sides in the conflict. Here&rsquo;s what each condition means:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Setback</strong>: If the heroes suffer a Setback vines (or Gospog) get caught in the propeller and the boat slows down&hellip;allowing another 2 Gospog to clamber aboard each Villain turn until the jam is cleared. To clear it a character must move to the back of the boat and make a DN 10 Strength test. If the villains suffer a Setback remove one Gospog as the vines growing on it get caught in the propeller and it is pulled in and ground into small chunks!</li>\n<li><strong>Confused</strong>: The Heroes may not activate Destiny Cards. They may still earn them and play them into their Action Pools (see @Compendium[world.up-the-creek.LqYEn2OP1Oxe9XNi]{03 - Scene One: The Journey Begins}).</li>\n<li><strong>Up</strong>: The side with an Up rolls a die for tests, and then immediately adds another die regardless of the result!</li>\n<li><strong>Fatigue</strong>: Each hero immediately suffers 2 Shock (see Shock below). If the hero is wearing Armor with the Fatigues property she suffers 3 Shock instead, or more if the Armor lists a larger number! Gospog are immune to Shock, so a Fatigued result doesn&rsquo;t hamper them at all!</li>\n<li><strong>Inspiration</strong>: Each character on the affected side recovers 2 Shock. See @Compendium[world.up-the-creek.JN6ZbILajAthoEBS]{Damage}.</li>\n<li><strong>Surge</strong>: The reality of the Living Land pushes against Storm Knights who have contradictory items. Each player rolls a d20. On a 1, a character with a contradiction Disconnects (see below). The Realm Runner is carrying items that don&rsquo;t just exceed the Living Land&rsquo;s axioms, they exceed his own! He Disconnects on a roll of 1-4 so long as he&rsquo;s carrying them.</li>\n<li><strong>Flurry</strong>: Resolve all actions for that side normally. Then every character on that side acts again!</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Approved Actions</h3>\n<p>At the bottom of the card one or two of the following are listed: Attack, Defend, Intimidate, Maneuver, Taunt, and Trick, plus &ldquo;Any&rdquo; and &ldquo;Any Multi-Action&rdquo;. If a character attempts the listed action and succeeds the player draws a new Destiny Card. Introduce the basics of Actions below, and then add the explanations for Defend, Interactions (Intimidate, Maneuver, Taunt, Trick), Multi-Actions, and the Law of Savagery only when the relevant Approved Action comes up for the turn.</p>\n<h3>The Law of Savagery and All-Out Attacks</h3>\n<p>If Attack is an Approved Action, describe the All-Out Attack special option to players. This option is only available to hand to hand attacks, so melee weapons or unarmed combat. The attacker gains a +4 bonus to hit, but becomes Very Vulnerable (+4) in return. The option is always available, but the Law of Savagery makes it especially tempting when Attack is Approved: a hit with an All-Out Attack gains an extra Bonus Die (+1 BD) of damage&hellip;in addition to any other dice granted by a Good or Outstanding success. Note that Villains, even Gospog, take advantage of this option when Attack is Approved!</p>\n<h3>Steps and Dilemmas</h3>\n<p>Along the side are letters (A, B, C, and D) or a Dilemma (Complication, Critical Problem, and Potential Setback). Ignore these for now, they aren&rsquo;t used until a Dramatic Skill Resolution starts. Dramatic Skill Resolutions are covered as a part of @Compendium[world.up-the-creek.jpwOVLoQXh4xjn7q]{04 - Scene Two: Land Ho!}.</p>"}
{"_id":"LEEgqVrw5S1BDd7a","name":"Friendly Fire","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.3UWmgP16pWaKSCqG"}},"content":"<p>Firing a gun or other ranged attack into melee combat is tricky. If the total on the dice for the attack is even, the attack is against the Defense of the intended target and proceeds normally. If the total for the roll is odd, the attack is against the Defense of another random participant! A character may move out of melee combat at the expense of becoming Vulnerable (+2), so try to time hero actions so friends pull away from the gospog before someone opens fire on them!&nbsp;</p>"}
{"_id":"LqYEn2OP1Oxe9XNi","name":"03 - Scene One: The Journey Begins","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.wrmBPou5JerezE2v"}},"content":"<p>Read aloud or paraphrase the following:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>&ldquo;The reality storms around this part of the Pacific are calm for the moment, and no wandering dinosaurs or sea monsters attack during the trip into the bay. As you cross over into the Living Land you get goosebumps and feel the crackling energy or reality that only Storm Knights are attuned to.&rdquo;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2>Axioms &amp; World Laws</h2>\n<p>Reveal @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.XEYr34ZyAggBFLI8]{The Living Land Table Tent} journal entry to the players. Then, point out the features set out in @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.MXSfDu4jcJQFdRcT]{Axioms and World Laws}.&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Cosm Cards</h3>\n<p>Deal each player one Living Land Cosm Card. These cards may be played at ANY time, and often grant the player or all the heroes more Possibilities. Some ideas for dealing with specific Cosm cards in this adventure may be found in @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.z8l7gqSGveLarn4X]{Cosm Cards}.</p>\n<h2>The Adventure Continues...</h2>\n<p>Reveal the map of the boat to the players and ask them to decide who&rsquo;s piloting the boat. Let each player position their character around the ship and describe what they&rsquo;re doing. To place themselves on the boat, have the players drag their character from the Actor tab onto the map. This will create a token for their character.</p>\n<p>None of the characters have a water vehicles skill so it doesn&rsquo;t really matter who steers, but only a modern character like the Realm Runner understands how it operates and can operate it without additional contradiction. One or more characters is probably keeping a lookout. Good! They all get to roll a test for that shortly.</p>\n<p>Read aloud or paraphrase the following:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>&ldquo;Your boat motors past the crumbling ruins of Astoria. A few vine&ndash;covered skyscrapers remain standing in the distance. Pterodactyls swoop around them and nest in the upper floors. The rest of the city is nothing but ruins covered by a thick canopy of jungle. It&rsquo;s as if the city were bombed a hundred years ago and nature has reclaimed the remains&mdash;except it happen practically overnight. It&rsquo;s hot and humid in the Living Land, even though the air at sea was cold and brisk.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;The jungle trees are massive, and branches stretch all the way across the wide Columbia river to form a dense canopy overhead. Vines dangle down into the river and an occasional low&ndash;hanging branch scrapes alone the side of the vessel as it moves upriver.&rdquo;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2>FIRST TESTS</h2>\n<p>Have each character make a find test to see if they spot trouble while moving up the river. Have every character complete the test as described below, just to teach how tests work.&nbsp; This is a fundamental game mechanic and comes up often, so take the time to get everyone used to it now!</p>\n<h3>Skill Bases</h3>\n<p>Every character has a find skill, found in their list of skills on the character sheet.Each skill starts with a base, determined by the appropriate attribute. For find, that&rsquo;s Mind. Then there are a number of &lsquo;skill adds&rsquo; that get added to the attribute, usually one to three, to give a total found to the right. The number to the right is the one that matters, but it&rsquo;s worth breaking down where that number comes from! For example, The Realm Runner has a Mind of 8, and +1 add in find, for a total base of 9.</p>\n<h3>Dice Rolls</h3>\n<p>The player should click on the Find skill on their character sheet. This will roll a d20, and then generate a number called an Action Total. Both the d20 roll and the action total will be displayed in chat.</p>\n<p>The Torg Eternity system calculates the Action Total by doing the following: it compares the number to @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.BGpU76zitnb1LnzH]{The Bonus Chart}. The number generated is called the Bonus, and gets added to the base above for a final value. Note that the Bonus may be negative! A 1 on the first die always fails. A 10 or 20 is special. Roll another d20 and add the result to the first. A 1 on these extra dice doesn&rsquo;t automatically fail, but another 10 or 20 does generate another extra die roll! Added together dice can generate a huge bonus&mdash;the chart goes to 60 and beyond!</p>\n<h3>Unskilled Tests</h3>\n<p>Everyone has find, but for other tests it may matter if a character has adds in the skill or not. If not a roll is still possible, just use the attribute for the base, but without adds the test is labelled as Unskilled: a result of 10 generates another die as usual, but a result of 20 does not.</p>\n<h3>Difficulty Number (DN)</h3>\n<p>The target Difficulty Number (DN) for any test is 10 unless otherwise specified. If the base plus bonus equals 10 or more, the test is a success. If the result is less than 10 the test failed. Generating a result that&rsquo;s five or more than the DN is a Good result, and may have extra effects. Generating a result 10 or more beyond the DN is an Outstanding result. Thus for this find test, a total of 10&ndash;14 is a success, 15&ndash;19 is a Good success, and 20+ is Outstanding.</p>\n<h3>Bonuses add to Bonuses: The Bonus Chart</h3>\n<p>Players may wish to play a Destiny card at this point to improve their tests. An Action or Willpower card adds a +3 bonus, or a Supporter card adds a +3 bonus to someone else&rsquo;s test. To do so, click on the +3 Card button at the bottom of the chat message that displays the original action total. Note that the +3 is to the Bonus generated&hellip;not the result of the dice. Likewise if a character declared they were messing around and not paying attention the GM may apply a &ndash;2 Penalty to the find test, affecting the end result but not the die roll.</p>\n<h3>Dice Add to Dice: Spending Possibilities</h3>\n<p>If someone rolls poorly now is a great time to introduce one function of the Possibility points that each player has. Spend a point and click on the Possibility button at the end of the chat message showing your action total to roll another d20 and ADD the result to the first one! If this new die rolls less than a 10, Foundry will treat it as minimum +10 instead. If it rolls an actual 10 or 20, it will add another die roll as usual! Foundry will automatically recheck the Bonus Chart to get the new number to add to the base. Remember, a bonus like +3 or &ndash;2 adds to the final result, never the die rolls&hellip;but new dice from 10s, 20s, or Possibilities always add together to generate the value from the Bonus Chart.</p>\n<h3>Failure</h3>\n<p>If a character fails this test they are Stymied, a condition that gives them a &ndash;2 on all tests until the end of their next Action.</p>\n<h3>Success (10 or Better)</h3>\n<p>Anyone that generates a total of 10 or more on their find test sees a logjam of flotsam, decomposing jungle foliage, and scattered human bodies washing downriver. The boat easily maneuvers to avoid the larger logs, but the corpses begin to scream and clamber up onto the ship&rsquo;s deck! Combat begins as below, but at least the character is ready.</p>\n<h3>Good (15 or Better)</h3>\n<p>Just like a success, but the character saw the twitching limbs of the corpses and realized early that these weren&rsquo;t dead bodies, they were Gospog! Gospog are horrifying creatures made by the invaders by planting strange seeds in the bodies of those killed during the invasion. When the Gospog begin to scream any character with a Good success or better gets a +2 bonus on the Fear test (see below).</p>\n<h3>Outstanding (20 or Better)</h3>\n<p>Like a Good success, but the character was on guard enough to warn the boat to maneuver enough away from the bodies that the gospog take extra time getting aboard. When the Encounter starts (see below) if the Villains would have acted first they merely arrive around the ship rather than gaining actions. If a character has an Alertness Destiny Card and wants to spend it, treat it as if someone got an Outstanding result!</p>\n<h2>FIRST ENCOUNTER</h2>\n<p>Gospog lurch into the boat, trying to bite and rend the flesh of the living! There are two Gospog of the First Planting for each hero present. The first thing to do is to draw a Drama card and place it on the desktop to set the initiative and any special conditions for the turn.</p>\n<p>There are two Gospog of the First Planting for each Storm Knight. Drag and drop the Gospog from the Actor tab onto the outside of the boat.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-actors.muGYv1XZDojsyEfv]{Gospog of the First Planting}(2 per Storm Knight).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Additionally, you should show the @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.6VffoCRaJ8eZOPi1]{Gospog Threat Stand} to the players.</p>\n<h3>Drama Cards</h3>\n<p>Torg Eternity is played in scenes, and each scene is either Standard or Dramatic. This is a Standard Scene, so check whether the Heroes act first or the Villains do. Note that if anyone gained an Outstanding result on the find test the villains don&rsquo;t get to act if they go first! When the heroes go, each may act in any order desired, just coordinate with one another. Once everyone has finished acting the round is complete, flip over a new Drama Card for the next round.</p>\n<p>On the same line of the card that says which side acts first, you may see a condition that affects the entire side. See @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.KTres6vCn1T1KcKO]{Drama Cards} for a description of what each condition means.</p>\n<h3>The Action Pool</h3>\n<p>Until an encounter begins there&rsquo;s no limit on trading or playing Destiny Cards. However, once battle is joined things get trickier! Cards may only be played or traded from each character&rsquo;s Action Pool, and that pool starts off empty. At the end of each turn after the character acts, the player may put one Destiny Card in their pool by marking it (see @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.9l3qvlJ9eFizcEor]{Managing Cards}). It may be played immediately, or at any time after that. Putting a card in the Action Pool isn&rsquo;t playing it, but now it&rsquo;s available to be played or traded!</p>\n<h3>Basic Actions</h3>\n<p>When the heroes (or the Gospog) act they have several basic options.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.prbDBaVAlMkytvbo]{Moving} involves walking or running up to the speed on their character sheet.</li>\n<li>An @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.5ax6sbR4BFCqp7IN]{Attack}, which attempts to physically damage a target.</li>\n<li>The Storm Knight may also @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.sHmYbJh6Wu7E9ayo]{Defend}, in a concentrated effort to avoid damage.</li>\n<li>An @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.UdOHo3I4piwEd6vO]{Interaction Attack} attempts to place the opponent at a disadvantage using cunning words and/or actions.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When a Storm Knight or Gospog is hit, follow the rules for @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.JN6ZbILajAthoEBS]{Damage}.</p>\n<p>Other rules that may come into play during the encounter include the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>&nbsp;@Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.B2TKLzGGeXvc1ZU1]{Multi-Actions} apply when a character attempts more than one action at once.</li>\n<li>A Storm Knight or Gospog may also attack @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.qCTdErWd4Yq5gH9h]{Multi-Targets}.</li>\n<li>A Storm Knight may have a weapon that does @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.plqbdUM5mBUfGxdu]{Armor Piercing} damage.</li>\n<li>A Storm Knight may have a firearm that utilizes the @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.7Af9s2g1GlkytrNY]{Short Burst}.</li>\n<li>A Primitive Warrior may want to utilize her @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.t4psjpSrhSSYXxOQ]{Sabretooth Cat}.</li>\n<li>If a Storm Knight using any high-tech equipment (over Tech Level 7) rolls a 1, that character must test for @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.OuHaBxUl8n5lojot]{Disconnection}.</li>\n<li>If a Storm Knight sufferws more than three wounds, the Storm Knight must test for @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.4hN0xAsql86XWwEY]{Defeat}.</li>\n<li>When attacking with Gospog, the GM may want to consider utilizing a @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.wa3TfGPytgJyjSFO]{Combined Attack}.</li>\n<li>If a Storm Knight attempts to fire a gun or other ranged attack into melee combat, they take a risk of injuring an ally by @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.LEEgqVrw5S1BDd7a]{Friendly Fire}.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>THE END OF THE BATTLE</h2>\n<p>When the last Gospog is defeated everyone unmarks any cards left in their Action Pools. If a player has more than four cards, discard down to four. This marks the end of the scene, so any player with fewer than four cards draws back up to four. Any Shock suffered recovers automatically.</p>\n<p>Proceed to @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.jpwOVLoQXh4xjn7q]{04 - Scene Two: Land Ho!}.</p>"}
{"_id":"MXSfDu4jcJQFdRcT","name":"Axioms and World Laws","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.ew09Zjnywuwxkm9p"}},"content":"<p>Axioms measure what&rsquo;s plentiful in a reality, and what&rsquo;s &ldquo;impossible.&rdquo;</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Magic Axiom</strong>: The low number means magic doesn&rsquo;t exist here. The only character with any magic is the Realm Runner, who has a magic potion. Carrying it creates a &ldquo;Contradiction&rdquo;, which means he&rsquo;s out of step with reality at risk of @Compendium[world.up-the-creek.OuHaBxUl8n5lojot]{Disconnection}.</li>\n<li><strong>Social Axiom</strong>: The low number means higher level civilization isn&rsquo;t supported here. Democracy doesn&rsquo;t make sense to people attuned to the realm&hellip;but following the strongest hunter and taking what you want does! If any Storm Knight had Psionic powers, they would be contradictory here.</li>\n<li><strong>Spirit Axiom</strong>: The high number means faith has tangible effects in the Living Land. Gods are real, and praying for miracles works without contradiction!</li>\n<li><strong>Tech Axiom</strong>: This is the number most of the Storm Knights present care about. Advanced technology is contradictory here. Each character has an Axiom listed for their items. If the number is above 6 the item is a Contradiction within the Living Land, so using it opens the character to the possibility of Disconnection.</li>\n<li><strong>Law of Savagery</strong>: When battle rages, things get bloody in the Living Land. Don&rsquo;t dwell on the exact meaning of this rule until combat starts.&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>Law of Life:</strong> Wounds heal quickly here, and dead matter decomposes rapidly as well. It&rsquo;s unlikely for this rule to come up during the game, but if it does, see @Compendium[world.up-the-creek.4hN0xAsql86XWwEY]{Defeat}.</li>\n<li><strong>Law of Wonders</strong>: Lost things turn up unexpectedly in the Living Land, and stone and metal buildings that would normally crumble into rubble tend to remain standing as vine covered monoliths instead.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When Storm Knights visit different realms affected by other realities, these axioms and laws change to reflect what&rsquo;s easy to do here, and what&rsquo;s hard.</p>"}
