{"_id":"plqbdUM5mBUfGxdu","name":"Armor Piercing","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.N0Qlctx7umJTVEuc"}},"content":"<p>The Electric Warrior&rsquo;s Electric Katana and the Monster Hunter&rsquo;s Adamant Shells each piece armor. Armor Piercing negates Armor adds to Toughness. Gospog and Edeinos Warriors don&rsquo;t have armor, so there&rsquo;s no effect. The Tyrannosaur&rsquo;s Toughness has 3 Armor, so the katana would knock it down to Toughness 18, and the Adamant Shells to Toughness 17.</p>"}
{"_id":"prbDBaVAlMkytvbo","name":"Moving","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.JiGP9oyvvLlUCnJr"}},"content":"<p>Moving isn&rsquo;t an action, but happens on each character&rsquo;s turn along with the action. Each character has a Move listed in meters. On the provided map each square is 2 meters. A character may &ldquo;Run&rdquo; three times the base number of meters, but suffers a &ndash;2 penalty on any test for an action.</p>"}
{"_id":"qCTdErWd4Yq5gH9h","name":"Multi-Targets","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.xdrk6Ham3C1W9VNZ"}},"content":"<p>Similar to Multi-Actions, an attack or interaction attack may target multiple foes. If the weapon used requires ammunition, it needs at least one shot for each target. Every extra target for the attack is a &ndash;2 penalty, so attempting to trick three Gospog at once is a &ndash;4 penalty. Roll <em><strong>once</strong></em>, apply the bonus, then compare the result to each target&rsquo;s Defense separately and resolve the effects individually. This a good concept to introduce during the second round of combat, once players have gotten comfortable with regular attacks and tests.&nbsp;</p>"}
{"_id":"s83mmSqxTbd0JI1R","name":"01- About this Adventure","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.EhUT5u82lsOLxXfj"}},"content":"<p>This Quickstart is intended as a one hour introduction to the concepts and rules of Torg Eternity, as well as a tutorial for GMs and players on how to play Torg Eternity in Foundry. It&rsquo;s designed to walk both the GM and the players through the rules and Founrdy system together, adding layers as it goes. This gives a general feel for gameplay, but there are many more character options and realms to explore in the full game!&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Setting Up</h2>\n<p>Before you begin play, you will need to prepare the Destiny Deck and the Living Land Cosm deck:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Make sure that you have installed the basic Drama Deck, the basic Destiny Deck, and the Living Land cosm deck. This can be done from the Settings menu for the Torg Eternity System.</li>\n<li>After all players are logged in the Foundry game, but before beginning play, be sure that your players have full access to the Destiny deck and the Living Land Cosm deck. To to so, go to the settings tab for the Unofficial Card Support module and click on Deck Settings. From there, make sure all your players are allowed access to draw, view, and discard. Details on how to manage the decks can be found in @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.9l3qvlJ9eFizcEor]{Managing Cards}.</li>\n<li>For this Quickstart, delete the following cards from the Destiny Deck: Martyr, Flurry, Master Plan, Connection, Idea, Attuned, Glory, Romance, Nemesis, Reality Surge, and Maelstrom. The quickest way to do this is to take all of those cards into your own hand and then delete each one.</li>\n<li>After you have taken the above steps, shuffle the Destiny Deck and the Living Land Cosm deck.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>To get started with the adventure, proceed to @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.4g5ZJWG18rjdUQ2P]{02 - Introduction}.</p>","img":""}
{"_id":"sHmYbJh6Wu7E9ayo","name":"Defend","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.el2TAJ1281IGcBPB"}},"content":"<p>A hero may use their turn to defend themselves instead of attacking, even if the Villains go first. Click on the Defenses heading on the character sheet to roll against the Bonus Chart and generate a bonus, with a minimum result of +1 (even if the die roll is a 1). That bonus is added to any Defense against attacks or interaction attacks for the rest of the round. If Defend is an Approved Action, the player gains a Destiny card the first time a foe attempts an attack and misses.</p>"}
{"name":"Sabretooth Cat","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.INZvazTjjcVtGd1J"}},"content":"<p>The Primitive Warrior has a &ldquo;pet&rdquo; who acts on her turn. The player controls the cat as well, and tracks its Shock and Wounds separately. The cat doesn&rsquo;t have Possibilities of its own, but the player may spend the Primitive Warrior&rsquo;s Possibilites to the creature&rsquo;s tests or soak damage done to it.</p>\n<p>If the player isn&rsquo;t sure what to do, suggest that the cat make a @Compendium[world.up-the-creek.wa3TfGPytgJyjSFO]{Combined Attack} against the same target, which gives the Primitive Warrior a +1 to the test. If Maneuver is an Approved Action suggest the cat set up a foe for the Primitive Warrior to finish off. This shows Interaction Attacks and she even gets the Destiny Card on a success. For anything else, the Sabretooth Cat&rsquo;s statistics are included in the same manner as the other threats.</p>","_id":"t4psjpSrhSSYXxOQ"}
{"_id":"wa3TfGPytgJyjSFO","name":"Combined Attack","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.Dj1RCzyiYGOsBdTT"}},"content":"<p>With so many gospog, it&rsquo;s likely several attack the same hero each round. When this occurs, only roll once for the group, but they gain a +1 bonus if two are attacking, +2 if three are attacking, and +3 if four to six all swarm the same opponent.</p>"}
{"_id":"z8l7gqSGveLarn4X","name":"Cosm Cards","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.iH7lNn81snQKmk3n"}},"content":"<p>Each player has a Cosm Card they may play at any time. Cosm Cards don&rsquo;t need to go into the Action Pool, that&rsquo;s just for Destiny Cards. Depending upon which cards are played, an adventure can turn out very differently! Here&rsquo;s a few hints on how to handle the Cosm Cards within this adventure.</p>\n<h3>Dino Attack!</h3>\n<p>The dreaded Tyrannosaur stalks the area. Even if the card is played early, the GM may have it appear at any time during the act, so don&rsquo;t have it attack the boat. The best time for an appearance is on the second round of the Dramatic Skill Resolution. It focuses on the heroes, but it may gobble up an edeinos or two if they suffer a Setback!</p>\n<h3>Lost Treasure</h3>\n<p>An out of place rubber muck boot lying in the mud draws attention. Upon investigation it turns out the boot is filled with gold dust. A Storm Knight with a successful DN 14 scholar (based on Mind) test might remember doubtful legends of such a boot lost in 1857. The gold has no effect on this adventure, but the Delphi Council or the Storm Knights might get use out of it later!</p>\n<h3>Law of Decay</h3>\n<p>In general award no Possibilities if the item chosen is cosmetic or unlikely to impact the adventure. Award 1 Possibility for backup weapons or ammunition. Award 2 Possibilities for most Armor, the Realm Runner&rsquo;s special items, or the Machete since it&rsquo;s survival boost might come in handy during the Dramatic Skill Resolution. A character&rsquo;s trademark weapon or Armor that provides +4 protection is worth 3 Possibilities!</p>\n<h3>Perils of the Living Land</h3>\n<p>The river is blocked by a new waterfall that the boat can&rsquo;t navigate. Award each Storm Knight 1 Possibility for the trouble, but they&rsquo;ve got a longer hike ahead of them to reach the stelae. Have them attempt a DN 14 survival test (one leader, others may do a @Compendium[world.up-the-creek.wa3TfGPytgJyjSFO]{Combined Attack}). If it fails, each Storm Knight suffers a Fatigue result (see @Compendium[world.up-the-creek.KTres6vCn1T1KcKO]{Drama Cards}) on the way to the encounter, and that Shock is still in effect when the encounter starts.</p>\n<h3>The Deep Mist</h3>\n<p>The group only has four rounds to complete the Dramatic Skill Resolution thanks to getting lost. Award each Storm Knight 2 Possibilities for the extra trouble.</p>"}
{"_id":"4g5ZJWG18rjdUQ2P","name":"02 - Introduction","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.z4J9hKbVShYvJ8IY"}},"content":"<p><strong>Location</strong>: Briefing room aboard the USS Theodore Roosevelt.</p>\n<p>Read aloud or paraphrase the following:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>&ldquo;Three months ago the world as we knew it changed. Strange bridges descended from the sky in various places around the planet, and where they landed reality itself bent and changed. Invaders crossed the bridges and now they&rsquo;re turning Earth into something else, piece by piece. The clash of realities creates storms, and a few special people are changed by the storm. They become heroes, the best version of themselves from this or an alternate reality. You and those seated in this room are some of those people.&rdquo;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The base Foundry system for Torg Eternity includes 16 archetype characters as a part of its built-in compendium. Have each player select from among the following archetypes by dragging the archetype from the compendium into the Actor tab: Electric Samurai, Reality Raider, Prmitive Warrior, Masked Crusader and/or Monster Hunter. Other archetypes can be used, but detailed instructions on how to handle them are not incluced in this adventure. The background tab of each character sheet explains who the character is, and what they do. Have each player select a name for their character, and let them describe who is seated in the briefing room and greet one another. Delay any questions about what statistics mean or what the Tactics section refers to for now.</p>\n<p>On each sheet call everyone&rsquo;s attention to the Moment of Crisis. This is the exact instant the hero changed from an ordinary person into a Storm Knight. This happens when a person is faced with danger and makes an active choice to help others or fight to repulse an invading reality. When this happens raw energy floods into the hero, and they gain the power to bend reality to their own will. In game terms that means they each get Possibility tokens and a hand of Destiny cards.</p>\n<h3>Possibility Energy</h3>\n<p>Each player should set their availiable possiblities to three (3). They can spend these to avoid damage or boost their dice rolls. Don&rsquo;t explain the specifics of either of those uses yet, but this indicates the amount of power they have to &ldquo;push back&rdquo; against reality. When a player does something that delights everyone at the table, give them another Possibility point as a reward. Note: The Realm Runner starts with four possibilities instead of three.</p>\n<h3>Destiny Cards</h3>\n<p>Each player should draw four (4) Destiny cards. For detailed instructions on how this is done, see @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.9l3qvlJ9eFizcEor]{Managing Cards}.</p>\n<p>Each card explains what it does, but may not make sense until the first tests below. Outside of combat these cards may be played or traded between players (one for one) at any time.</p>\n<h2>THE MISSION BRIEFING</h2>\n<p>An officer (Captain McDonnell if asked) briefs the Storm Knights on the mission. Read the following aloud.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>&ldquo;The Delphi Council has asked us to support a reconnaissance mission into the alien zone that&rsquo;s taken over both coastlines of North America. The &lsquo;Living Land&rsquo; they&rsquo;re calling it. If we send regular troops into the zone their weapons malfunction and some even revert to a primitive mental state. But you Storm Knights aren&rsquo;t as severely affected by altered reality, so we&rsquo;re depending on you. These invading zones are bordered by stone monoliths called stelae. We&rsquo;re studying these stelae to figure out how we can use them against the invaders&mdash;but first we have to locate them!</p>\n<p>&ldquo;Your mission is simple, but not necessarily easy. We have a converted tour boat for you to take inland. Get as far as you can up the Columbia river, past the ruins of Astoria. There are survivors living there who got word of a stela somewhere inland, maybe a backup of some kind. When you reach the wreckage of the Route 433 bridge go ashore, find that stela, and determine if it&rsquo;s just stone or something else. Don&rsquo;t try to destroy it at this time, we just want its coordinates and a &ldquo;feeling&rdquo; from Storm Knights on whether it&rsquo;s dangerous or not.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;Any questions?&rdquo;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3>Potential Questions and Answers</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>What can we expect in the Living Land?</strong> Conditions and brutal and primitive. Technology much beyond spears and bows doesn&rsquo;t work for ordinary people&mdash;at least not for long&mdash;and metal rusts at an accelerated rate if left unattended. Most affected humans become ruled by instinct and savage impulses. The invaders there are lizardmen known as edeinos. Oh, and watch out for the dinosaurs.</li>\n<li><strong>What about the survivors in Astoria? </strong>They have a walled community built around a house made famous by some movie. Some landmarks resist the change in reality, and around them are pockets of unaltered &ldquo;Core Earth&rdquo; where people can stay. Astoria has one of these.</li>\n<li><strong>Is the boat armed?</strong> No, but you Storm Knights are. This is a reconnaissance mission, not an assault, and this is just a converted tourist boat meant for transportation and little else.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Once any questions are answered, proceed to @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.LqYEn2OP1Oxe9XNi]{03 - Scene One: The Journey Begins}.</p>"}
{"_id":"s83mmSqxTbd0JI1R","name":"01- About this Adventure","permission":{"default":0,"A9LyAqagoJJU3gDH":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.EhUT5u82lsOLxXfj"}},"content":"<p>This Quickstart is intended as a one hour introduction to the concepts and rules of Torg Eternity, as well as a tutorial for GMs and players on how to play Torg Eternity in Foundry. It&rsquo;s designed to walk both the GM and the players through the rules and Founrdy system together, adding layers as it goes. This gives a general feel for gameplay, but there are many more character options and realms to explore in the full game!&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Setting Up</h2>\n<p>Before you begin play, you will need to prepare the Destiny Deck and the Living Land Cosm deck:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Make sure that you have installed the basic Drama Deck, the basic Destiny Deck, and the Living Land cosm deck. This can be done from the System menu for Torg Eternity.</li>\n<li>After all players are logged in the Foundry game, but before beginning play, be sure that your players have full access to the Destiny deck and the Living Land Cosm deck. To to so, go to the settings tab for the Unofficial Card Support module and click on Deck Settings. From there, make sure all your players are allowed access to draw, view, and discard. Details on how to manage the decks can be found in @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.9l3qvlJ9eFizcEor]{Managing Cards}.</li>\n<li>For this Quickstart, delete the following cards from the Destiny Deck: Martyr, Flurry, Master Plan, Connection, Idea, Attuned, Glory, Romance, Nemesis, Reality Surge, and Maelstrom. The quickest way to do this is to take all of those cards into your own hand and then delete each one.</li>\n<li>After you have taken the above steps, shuffle the Destiny Deck and the Living Land Cosm deck.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>To get started with the adventure, proceed to @Compendium[te002-up-the-creek.up-the-creek-journals.4g5ZJWG18rjdUQ2P]{02 - Introduction}.</p>","img":""}
